{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_fontaine_ver01/data/sn87055779/00517016913/1927060401/0153.xml":{"full_text":"t\nSODDEN REACTION\nSETS NEW RECORD\nON STOCK MARKET\nNervous Liquidation by Re\ncent Hea\\7 Buyers\nCauses Selling. 7 I\nt,\nBy ELMER C. YVALZER\nIn i led News Staff Financial Editor j\nNEW YORK, June 3.\u2014In the most!\nactive session since Feb. 9, stocks on\nthe New York stock exchange Friday\nreacted sharply following a steady\nstart in early dealings.' Tire number\not issues traded exceeded 670, a new\nrecord for breadth of the market,\nwhile total transactions were above\n2,600,000. j\nNews of the day had little real ef\nfect, the selling being a combination\nof nervous liquidation by recent\nheavy buyers, who sold to take profits,\nweek-end realizing and a general\ntechnical reaction. However, now\nthat the ball has definitely started j\nrolling in the other direction, it is i\ndifficult to hazard just how far the j\nreaction will be carried.\nThere was talk of the proposed j\naction of the Federal Reserve bank\ndeferring indefinitely a reduction in\nthe rediscount rate at the New York\ncenter. This, together with outlook\nfor a large increase in brokerage loans\nnext week and further firmness in\nmoney, caused additional nervousness.\nOne of the reasons, which had kept\nthe rediscount rate at four per cent\n.followin'' the reduction in the rate by\nthe bank of England, was the fear\nthat speculation would run to undue\nproportions. Should a bad reaction\ndevelop it is quite likely the reserve\nboard would reconsider their de\ncision and cut the figure to 314 per\ncent.\nMoney Conditions Stiller.\nMoney conditions have been stlffer\nthan many had anticipated. How\never transactions involving more than\n$500.000,000 caused banks to withdraw\nfunds heavily to meet their first of\nthe month requirements. Now that\nthis period of stringency is over,\nmoney will begin to return to .the\nmarket. This should bolster up prices\nafter the present setback.\nAt the close Friday, U. S. Steel was\noff 1%, General Motors 1%. Allied\nChemical 2%, American Smelting\n3%, Baldwin 314, New York Central\n214, Western Maryland 2%. Wabash\n2%, Baltimore and Ohio 114, New\nHaven 114, Reading two, Hudson\nMotors 214, u. S. Rubber 2% and a\nhorde of others proportionately.\nCotton prices broke about $1.00 a\nbale, while wheat and all other ce\nreals were down sharply. Bonds held\nfairlv steady with trading quieter in\nall issues, including the U. S. govern\nment group, which has been very\nactive of late. Curb stocks reacted\nfrom their sharp advances on profiit\ntaking. Italian lira sold off the 10\npoints which it gained Thursday on\nnews that the Italian government\nwould stabilize the currency around\nthe present market quotation.\nBy THOMSON'-McKIXNOX.\nOpen High Low Close\nAllis Chalmers ..110 109%\nAme CanCo.51% 51% 50 50*4\nAmu Car-Fdy ...1U8% ..'106%\nA. 1. C.50% 00% 40 40%\nAmo Loco t\u2014....114% 114% 113% 113%\nAme Smelting ...104% 100%\nAme Steel Fdy 41% 44%\nAme Sugar .03 ..i. .01%\nAme Tel and Tel. .108% 100% 10S 108\nAme Wool 10 10% 18% 18%\nAnaconda Cop 40 45%\nAtl Gulf-W. I. 30% 00%\nAtchison \u2022\u2022..182% 181%\nBaldwin Loco ....223% 224% 210 219%\nit. and 0.123 123% 121% 121%\nBethlehem Steel 51% 50%\nCalifornia 1'etro 24% 24%\nCanadian Pacific. .180 .180\nC. and .0.181% 183% 181% 1S4Z\nC. M.-St. P. Com.. 14% 15% 14% 14%\nC. M.-St. 1*. I\u2019fd 24% 20% 24% 20%\nand N. W. 01 01 88% 89%\nK. I. and P. ..103% 105% 104 104%\nl\n\u2022u\nchili Copper 30\nColo Fuel-Iron 90% 91% 87\nChrysler Corp\nContinental Can\nCorn Products\nCrucible Steel\n1 tavison Cheui\nHodge Pfd .70\n30\n87%\n40% 40% 45% 4o%\n.07 07\n54% 54% 53% 53%\n.87 87\n'30 29%\n50% 54% 55\n.108% 108% 100% 107\n10% 10%\n200%,201\n50%\n19%\n92\nLrie Common\nFamous l\u2019lyers\nFisk Tire\nGeneral Asphalt\nGeneral Motors\nGoodrich Com\nGreat North Ore\nGreat North lty\nGulf States Steel.. 50% 51%\nHupp Mootr .20\nHudson Motor 83_\nJ nil pi. Oil-Gas 18%\nIndus