.\nSoviet Embassy Staff\nSets Sail for London\nBy United Press:\nLONDON, June 3.\u2014The Soviet\nembassy staff sailed from London, at\n2 a. m. today aboard the steamer\nYoushar. There was no demonstra\ntion.\nThe departure of the Soviet em\nbassy staff was caused by the break\ning of diplomatic relations between\nGreat' Britain and Soviet Russia.\nThe severance of relations was voted\nlast week by the House of Commons\nas a measure of the Baldwin gov\nernment, which charged Soviet trade\nemmissaries here with espionage.\nA\nAy v\nMaine Governor\nWill Speak Over\nRadio Tonight\nA story of forests and mountains\nind sea-shore and a personal invita\n;ion to spend the summer in Maine\nvill be offered to radio listeners to\nlight by Governor Ralph O. Brewster\n>f the most northeastern part of the\nUnited States tonight. He will ap\njear before the microphone of Sta\nton WMAQ, Chicago, at 7 o\u2019clock,\nCentral standard time, with a talk\nievoted to the wonders and natural\nresources, as well as the commercial\nispects of his commonwealth. Gov\nernor iBrewster is reputed to be one\nef the most forceful speakers among\nstate executives.\nA program of 13 selections, all tak\nen from the works of popular musical\neomedies not only of the present day,\njut also of a generation or two past,\nsvill be given tonight at 7 o\u2019clock Cen\ntal standard time, by the National\nLight Opera company. The concert\nsvill be heard through Stations WEAF,\nSTew York; WRC, Washington; WEEI,\nBoston; and WCAE, Pittsburgh.\nEverything by radio except the\nsmell of the tanbark is expected tc\nbe the menu from Station WFAA,\nDallas, Tex., tonight at 8:50 o\u2019clock\nCentral standard time, when a \u201cCir\ncus Night\u201d program is put on the air.\nAt 11:30 o\u2019clock, Station WFAA will\nbroadcast the entertainment from\nthe Palace theater of Dallas.\nA trio of string musicians, made up\nentirely of native hawaiians, will pre\nsent a program of current numbers as\nwell as little known Hawaiian selec\ntions tonight at 7 o\u2019clock, Central\nstandard time, through Stations WIP,\nPhiladelphia, and WGBS, New York.\nA mixed quartet from Dover, Del.,\nwill also take part in the program. At\n8:30 o\u2019clock, the Cole Trio, under the\ndirection of Lucius Cole, former mem\nber of the Philadelphia Symphony\norchestra, will present a program of\nclassical numbers.\nAnother of the \u201cPop\u201d concerts at\nSymphony hall, Boston, will be put\non the air tonight at 6:10 o\u2019clock,\nCentral standard time, by Station\nWBZ, Springfield, Mass.\nA program of German songs and\ninstrumental music will be heard\nduring the \u201cGerman Hour\u201d tonight at\n6 o\u2019clock. Central Standard time from\nStation WMCA, New York.\nMory Leaf, well-known portrait\npainter, who also has won fame for\nhimself as a radio entertainer from\nStation KNX, Los Angeles, win make\nhis first Eastern air appearance to\nnight at Station WGBS, New York,\nwith a program of dialect stories-and\nsongs, accompanied by himself on\nthe ukelele.\nPugilistic history will be turned\nbackward tonight at 7:30 o\u2019clock. Cen\ntral standard time when Station\nWGN, Chicago, revives the Mike Mc\nTigue-Battling Siki bout as one of its\n\u201cFamous Fights of All Time\u201d series.\nAt 8:30 o\u2019clock a program, \u201cIreland\u201d\nwill go on the air during the weekly\n\u201cOver the Hills and Far Away\u201d period.\nThe highest ranking officers of the\narmy and marine corps will be on the\nair tonight when the Second Division\nannual banquet is broadcast at 8\no\u2019clock, Central standard time, from\nStation WJZ, New York. Among the\nspeakers will be Assistant Secretary of\nWar Hanford MacNider; General\nJohn A. Lejeune; Major General\nJames G. Harbord; Major-General\nHanson E. Ely and Major-General j\nPreston Brown.\nThe Knights of Columbus Music\nclub of Independence, Mo., will broad\ncast a program through Station\nKLDS of that city tonight, beginning\nat 8 o\u2019clock, Central .standard time.\nA broadcast directed particularly to\nlisteners in the far north will be put\non the air tonight at 8:40 o\u2019clock,\nCentral standard time from Station\nWBZ, Springfield, Mass. It will con\ncern the moon\u2019s eclipse of June 15,\nvisible in that section.\nThe Westwood Women\u2019s Choral club\nwill present a program tonight\nthrough Station WOR, Newark, at\n6:45 o\u2019clock, Central standard time.\nBam dance music, old-time favor\nites, ukelele selections and numerous\nother features will make up the \u201cNa\ntional Barn Dance\u201d program which\nwill go on the air tonight from Sta\ntion WLS, Chicago, at 6 o\u2019clock, Cen\ntral standard time. r\nProminent speakers, both American\nand Indian will be heard tonight from\nStation WGL, New York, when the\nIndia Foundation dinner is broadcast\nat 8 o\u2019clock, Central standard time.\n(Copyright, 1927, Audio Service,\nChicago.)\nSilent Stations\nSATURDAY, JUNE 4\nCENTRAL WCBD. WGBF, WOAI,\nWAMD, WOI, KSO, KFLO, WFBE,\nKFUO.\nEASTERN WEBJ, WHN, WBAL,\nWRVA, WLWL, WGHP, WEAO, WFHH,\nWAIU, WTIC.\nFAR WEST\u2014KLX. KWSC, KOAC.\nSUNDAY, JUNE 5\nCENTRAL\u2014WIL, WOI, WGBF, WOS,\nKFH. WFBB.\nEASTERN CNRO, CNRT, CNRM,\nWABC, WAAXI, WHAZ, WHAM, WRVA,\nWRIT. WFHH, WNYC.\nFAR WEST KFOA, CNRR, CNRV,\nCNRE, KLX, CYJ.\n\nBest Features\nSATURDAY, JUNE 4\n:00 p. to. _\nWMCA (311) N. Y. German hour of\nmnsic.\nWJZ (455) N. Y. Marley Sherrls\u2019s Radio\nevening.\nWIP (508.2) Pblia. String band.\n:30 p. m.\nWGN (303) Chicago. Old Fight, Me\nTigue vs. Battling Sikl.\nWGBS (315.6) N. Y. \"\u201cThe Bad Time\nStory Man.\u201d\n:0O p. m. _\nKLDS (441) Independence. K. C. music\ndob recital.\nW^AA*\u2019(475.0) Dallas. Circus \"Night\nWBZ \"(333) Springfield. Messages re\ngarding Moon ecJlpse.\nSUNDAY, JUNE 5'r^4\n!:M p. *n.\nWJZ (435) S. Y\u00bb Roxy, and gang to\nchain. 1\n-1C,\n.fr\n\nWON\u2122303) Chicago. Baseball. Cubs ?i\nBoston, also WMAQ.\n3:45 p. m.\nWOK (405) Newark. 16th Inf. band.\n9:00 p. m.\nWIBO (228) C